<p><strong>Question:</strong> ‚ÄúI bought a bulldozer in July. Can I claim full-year capital allowance?‚Äù</p>
<p><strong>Answer:</strong> Yes! Capital allowance is not pro-rated in Malaysia. You claim full IA and AA in the year the equipment is first used for business, regardless of purchase month. However, the equipment must actually be in business use to qualify.</p>
<h3 id="scenario-2-equipment-upgrademodification">Scenario 2: Equipment Upgrade/Modification</h3>
<p><strong>Question:</strong> ‚ÄúI spent RM80,000 upgrading my bulldozer with GPS technology. Is this capital allowance eligible?‚Äù</p>
<p><strong>Answer:</strong> Yes, substantial improvements and upgrades qualify for capital allowance as separate assets or additions to the original cost basis. The upgrade must enhance the equipment‚Äôs capacity or efficiency for business use.</p>
<h3 id="scenario-3-partnershipjoint-venture-equipment">Scenario 3: Partnership/Joint Venture Equipment</h3>
<p><strong>Question:</strong> ‚ÄúOur joint venture bought equipment. How do we claim capital allowance?‚Äù</p>
<p><strong>Answer:</strong> The partner who legally owns the equipment claims capital allowance. If jointly owned, claim in proportion to ownership percentage. Ensure clear ownership documentation and coordinate with all partners‚Äô tax advisors.</p>
<h3 id="scenario-4-equipment-disposal">Scenario 4: Equipment Disposal</h3>
<p><strong>Question:</strong> ‚ÄúI sold my bulldozer after 3 years. What are the tax implications?‚Äù</p>
<p><strong>Answer:</strong> You‚Äôll have a balancing allowance (if sold below written-down value) or balancing charge (if sold above written-down value). This adjusts your total capital allowance claim to reflect actual depreciation experienced.</p>
